As well as being an important part of the United States Military history, you can defend your home and family with it. It is also easy for anyone in the family to shoot…. Very controllable, with plenty of punch ( more muzzle energy than a .44 mag.) .  Just as important, you can find parts for it if something needs to be replaced ( not always true with a commercially made rifle ).   Thank you for looking.

title: For Sale:  Finnish M39 Sako 1943 7.62x54R Rifle
postcontent: Finnish M39 rifle made by Sako in 1943. Bore is very nice with sharp rifling, metal finish is the nicest I've ever seen on an M39 and wood is also nice with no damage and oil finish. I've removed 90% of the cosmoline the Finns had it packed in but you can look forward to some brush and mineral spirits time with this one. Tang markings are Tula hammer, Soviet acceptance and proof stamps and a very worn circle which may be the remnants of the original Remington manufacturer (the US made Mosins for the Czar). See pic for barrel shank markings. Finns likely captured this one as a Russian Mosin 91 or 91/30 in the Finn Civil War of 1917 or the Winter War of 1939-40 and used the receiver to make an M39. The Finns never made a single receiver- all were Mosin purchases or captures that they converted to mutiple models including the M39. I have many more pics available- just ask. I have this up on GunBrkr for $499 but will sell to a local Montanan for $400 to avoid the shipping and FFL hassles. Extras include 10 stripper clips, Strike Hard Gear OD green bandolier, Allen quilted canvas case, and Finnish Army issue green leather sling. Plenty of cheap surplus ammo out there for these. FtF sale in Helena area preferred but I'm willing to drive some. Buyer must be adult Montana resident willing to sign bill of sale. Thanks for looking and message me with any questions.

Its integral flat-top mount, offers out-of-the-box compatibility with Civilian A3 and M4 carbines, and it attaches directly to any 1913 Picatinny rail for use on a variety of other systems as well. The 3x25 tactical scope has a .223 62 gr. BDC reticle. The illuminated center dot is extremely accurate for long range applications.  All of these features make this compact CQB-type tactical scope significantly superior to any red dot or EOtech type scopes, especially at long range, due to its higher magnification, uncomparable image quality, field of view, adjustable reticule image and reliability. This scope will function perfectly even with a dead battery. When the illumination is off, all the reticule lines appear in standard black and are razor sharp. The 3x25 tactical scope features a fully-illuminated reticule w/7 brightness levels for day/night use as well as a uniqe, 3-position, detachable Picatinny accessory collar for mounting lights, lasers and other accessories.
